 in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Llywelyn ap Dafydd was born about 1182, in Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Llywelyn ap Dafydd."},"et":{"about 1182–":"umbes 1182–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1200":"1200","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1182–":"noin 1182–Kuollut","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1182–Female":"1182–Kuollut","about 1182":"noin 1182","1200":"1200","about 1200":"noin 1200","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1182–":"environ 1182–Décédée","1182–Male":"1182–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1182–Female":"1182–Décédée","about 1182":"en